<h2 id="63">3. Saving the customer’s bank details</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can save the customer’s bank details in the <strong>Settings</strong> tab of a customer’s data record or delete them again as needed. Bank details are needed, e.g. for the payment method <a href="/en/order-processing/payment/managing-payment-methods#40">debit</a>. There is also an <a href="/en/order-processing/payment/managing-payments#10">import function</a> for bank details in plentymarkets. Contact a legal adviser for information about the current laws in your own country as well as in other countries of delivery.</p>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock important">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-important" title="Important"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Pay attention to subscription orders</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Note that the bank details saved here will also be used for subscription orders with the payment method <strong>Debit</strong>. If you delete bank details that are connected to such a subscription order, then the payment method in the <a href="/en/order-processing/orders/scheduler">scheduler</a> will be changed to the <a href="/en/order-processing/payment/managing-payment-methods#25">default payment method</a> for the particular client (store). The subscription order will then no longer be paid for as an automatic bank transfer. In such a case, only delete the bank details if absolutely necessary. If possible, save new bank details for the customer.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
